      <prefercite id="aspace_e880d8fefd7ee2652fce524d50b36ea1">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Henry Phelps Johnston Papers (MS 1400), Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_c29c31d1abcce5d79a551caa2a13cdb1">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Henry Phelps Johnston Papers include correspondence, a diary, printed material, and miscellaneous papers of Henry Phelps Johnston. The earliest papers date from Johnston's freshman year at Yale, but the bulk of the material documents Johnston's military service during the Civil War with the 15th Connecticut Volunteers and the Signal Corps. Johnston wrote regularly to his mother and sisters, and his letters in 1862 and 1863 describe the daily routine of camp life in Virginia. Letters from 1864 and 1865, after Johnston was promoted to a second lieutenancy, portray encounters with rebel troops in North Carolina and a meeting with his brother Frontis, a preacher in Lexington, North Carolina. A field dary (folder 7) documents Johnston's movements at the end of the war and his return to New Haven. Letters to Johnston's father (folder 4) describe his teaching position at the College of the City of New York. Johnston's incoming correspondence includes letters from Yale classmates: Frederic Adams, Melville Cox Day, Daniel Henry Chamberlain, Merritt Cicero Page, and Henry Hamlin Stebbins. Classmates relay information about friends, Yale activities, and their own career choices. There are also letter from Johnston's father, written from Mississippi.</p>
         <p>The papers were donated to the Yale Library by Henry S. Johnston in 1942 and 1943. Related papers of Johnston's mother and sisters will be found in the Johnston-Walker Family Papers, MS 949.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
